<p>This means that you can build a dynamic chart and automatically change the labels depending on what is shown on the chart.</p>

<p>I have demonstrated how to build dynamic data labels in a previous article if you are interested in using those in a chart.</p>

<p>In a post from March 2013 I demonstrated how to create Custom data labels in a chart.</p>

<p>Unfortunately, that technique worked only for bar and column charts.</p>

<p>You canÔÇÖt apply the same technique for an x y scatter chart, as far as I know.</p>

<p>Luckily the people at Microsoft have heard our prayers.</p>

<p>They have implemented a feature into Excel 2013 that allows you to assign a cell to a chart data point label a, in an x y scatter chart.</p>

<p>I will demonstrate how to do this for Excel 2013 and later versions and a workaround for earlier versions in this article.</p>

<p>How to apply custom data labels in Excel 2013 and later versions</p>

<p>This example chart shows the distance between the planets in our solar system, in an x y scatter chart.</p>

<p>The first 3 steps tells you how to build a scatter chart.</p>

<ol>
  <li>Select cell range B3:C11</li>
  <li>Go to tab ÔÇťInsertÔÇŁ</li>
  <li>Click the ÔÇťscatterÔÇŁ button</li>
  <li>Right click on a chart dot and left click on ÔÇťAdd Data LabelsÔÇŁ</li>
  <li>Right click on a dot again and left click ÔÇťFormat Data LabelsÔÇŁ</li>
  <li>
    <p>A new window appears to the right, deselect X and Y Value.</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>Enable ÔÇťValue from cellsÔÇŁ</p>
  </li>
  <li>Select cell range D3:D11</li>
